. Venkatasubramanian spent over two decades observing a credit market that specifically targets women in the Indian countryside of east-central Tamil Nadu. They found that paying off debts required labor, frequently involved sexual transactions, and shaped women's bodies and subjectivities. Bringing together ethnography, statistical surveys, and financial diaries, they offer for the first time a comprehensive theory for this sexual division of debt that goes far beyond the Indian case, exposing the ways capitalism transforms womanhood, and how this transformation in turn fuels capitalism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCapitalismxSocial aspectszIndiazTamil Nadu2DLC. 0aCapitalismxSocial aspectszIndiazTamil Nadu. 0aDebtzIndiazTamil Nadu2DLC. 0aDebtzIndiazTamil Nadu. 0aPoor womenzIndiazTamil NaduxSocial conditions2DLC. 0aPoor womenzIndiazTamil NaduxSocial conditions. 0aSex rolexEconomic aspectszIndiazTamil Nadu2DLC. 0aSex rolexEconomic aspectszIndiazTamil Nadu. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh  aBody.  aCapitalism.  aCaste.  aDebt.  aGender.  aIndia.  aKinship.  aSexuality.1 aKumar, Santosh, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aVenkatasubramanian, G., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079132740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363691040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503636910423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503636910/original  a978-3-11-079132-7  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles